XVGhOGibiVKhIX5NDBXzuopJGnsgXZgeLEhQnEeAa73J9VkdFvV0eWpzPR2ammAX9hqehhPgo5BRlk9jw97Oqg7U72KsyKTiJQLreZqMSXM4xB3QA20mdGKCY9rWY1nbsuWQ-S_YrWHHkq_0kd4sCGscTojFSjX6T-BIRg7OGG_SEjG_URuEKGv0HHFEbpFF-8JzaeygvV3xoLj\\\",\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering test configuration**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about whether to include test native reflect config. It's necessary for dynamic coverage, likely through JVM but not natively. I’m wondering if it's acceptable to add config for test fixtures since they shouldn't use reflection directly. The library’s public API does use reflection, and the user emphasizes tests must run under Native Image. To ensure everything works, I should add `reflect-config.json` with test inner classes to be safe.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Examining native-image config**\\\\n\\\\nI’m analyzing how the native-image config registers all declared fields and constructors, and how that might impact dynamic access coverage. This is specific to native runtime, while on JVM, dynamic coverage can still see call sites. The TCK native compile seems fine. I’m questioning whether reachability metadata tests check for test-specific metadata and if the reflect config syntax should be updated. Additionally, for Field#set, it seems I might need to ensure fields have write access and include \\\\\\\"allowWrite\\\\\\\": true in the reflect config.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering reflect configuration options**\\\\n\\\\nI’m exploring the use of `allDeclaredConstructors`: true and `allDeclaredFields`: true, along with possibly `allPublicMethods` for getters, though that might not be necessary. I need to ensure I have the correct binary names, keeping in mind the test class name does not include `$`, but the reflect config name does. I'm also wondering if making the fixture a public top-level class in its own file would help, though it seems that coverage in a dedicated Java test file might not be the best approach.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Thinking about nested classes and types**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering how public static nested classes are adequate, particularly focusing on private fields and inheritance. If fields are private, I'll need public getters. I might check if a List is of type List<String>. I'm also questioning whether using Date for timezone could be flaky, so I'm trying to avoid it. \\\\n\\\\nFor the TOML structure, I’m planning out things like `name`, `enabled`, and `port`, while parsing types like Long, Double, and Boolean, and ensuring that boxed types are used in ObjectDeserializer.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Reviewing ObjectDeserializerTest**\\\\n\\\\nI'm looking at the test for the ObjectDeserializer. The test should check if the TOML table can deserialize an object graph that includes inherited and private fields. I see that the `ServiceConfig` extends `BaseComponent`, which contains some methods like `getPort()`, while the `DatabaseConfig` has its own private fields.\\\\n\\\\nI wonder if I should make the test class public and consider using a text block for better readability. Also, I need to be cautious about Java source compatibility when checking settings in the repo.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_COkYpqyARpBNCX35FCWvCC1t|fc_0b4d47ddac0b60370169f4f719c3fc81a1aaac0ceb50cbef96\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"rg -n \\\"sourceCompatibility|JavaVersion|toolchain|languageVersion\\\" build.gradle tests/build.gradle tests/src/io.ous/jtoml/2.0.0/build.gradle settings.gradle | head -80\", \"timeout\": 10}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 712, \"output\": 944, \"cacheRead\": 26624, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 28280, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777661704557, \"responseId\": \"resp_0b4d47ddac0b60370169f4f708fe7881a19bf8e097e7257c87\"}, \"toolResults\": [{\"role\": \"toolResult\", \"toolCallId\": \"call_COkYpqyARpBNCX35FCWvCC1t|fc_0b4d47ddac0b60370169f4f719c3fc81a1aaac0ceb50cbef96\", \"toolName\": \"bash\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"rg: tests/build.gradle: No such file or directory (os error 2)\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777661722222}]}\n2744:  // NOTE: this version serves only as a placeholder and will be overridden by the CI when creating a new release\n2957:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_start\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"toolResult\", \"toolCallId\": \"call_6FZdGR4EGIkIS6p4vQhYSXS4|fc_0b4d47ddac0b60370169f4f71dbbc881a1b9b6b77d3b8583a3\", \"toolName\": \"read\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"/*\\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\\n *\\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\\n */\\nimport groovy.json.JsonSlurper\\n\\nimport org.graalvm.internal.tck.utils.CoordinateUtils\\nimport org.graalvm.internal.tck.utils.NativeImageConfigUtils\\nimport org.graalvm.internal.tck.utils.TestInfraLoggingUtils\\n\\nimport java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService\\nimport java.util.concurrent.Executors\\nimport java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit\\n\\nplugins {\\n    id 'base'\\n    id \\\"com.diffplug.spotless\\\" version \\\"6.3.0\\\"\\n    id \\\"org.graalvm.internal.tck-base\\\"\\n}\\n\\nallprojects {\\n    repositories {\\n        mavenCentral()\\n        mavenLocal()\\n    }\\n}\\n\\n// NOTE: this version serves only as a placeholder and will be overridden by the CI when creating a new release\\nproject.version(\\\"1.0.0-SNAPSHOT\\\")\\n\\n// gradle check\\nspotless {\\n    json {\\n        target(\\n                tck.metadataRoot.map { it.toString() + '/**/*.json' }.get(),\\n                tck.testRoot.map { it.toString() + '/**/*.json' }.get(),\\n                tck.repoRoot.map { it.toString() + '/stats/**/*.json' }.get()\\n        )\\n        targetExclude(\\n                tck.testRoot.map { it.toString() + '/**/build/**/*.json' }.get(),\\n                tck.repoRoot.map { it.toString() + '/.github/**/*.json' }.get()\\n        )\\n        gson()\\n                .indentWithSpaces(2)\\n                .sortByKeys()\\n                .version(\\\"2.9.0\\\")\\n    }\\n    String[] noHeaderDirs = [\\n            'native-build-tools/**', // external repository\\n            'docs/**',     // only .md files\\n            'metadata/**', // only .json files\\n            '**/build/**', // not relevant\\n            '**/.gradle/**', // not relevant\\n            'gradle/wrapper/**', // not relevant\\n            'tests/src/**/generated/**/*.java',\\n            'gradle/header.java',\\n            'gradle/header.sh',\\n    ]\\n\\n    java {\\n        target('**/*.java')\\n        targetExclude(*noHeaderDirs);\\n        // Place header before package/import/module\\n        licenseHeaderFile(\\\"$rootDir/gradle/header.java\\\", \\\"package |import |module \\\")\\n    }\\n\\n    groovy {\\n        target('**/*.groovy')\\n        targetExclude(*noHeaderDirs)\\n        // Place header before package/import\\n        licenseHeaderFile(\\\"$rootDir/gradle/header.java\\\", \\\"package |import \\\")\\n    }\\n    groovyGradle {\\n        // Build scripts (*.gradle)\\n        target('**/*.gradle')\\n        targetExclude(*noHeaderDirs)\\n        // Insert header at file start (works for any Gradle script layout)\\n        licenseHeaderFile(\\\"$rootDir/gradle/header.java\\\", \\\"(?m)^(import\\\\\\\\b|plugins\\\\\\\\b|buildscript\\\\\\\\b|apply\\\\\\\\b|rootProject\\\\\\\\b|pluginManagement\\\\\\\\b|dependencyResolutionManagement\\\\\\\\b)\\\")\\n    }\\n    format('shell') {\\n        target('**/*.sh')\\n        targetExclude(*noHeaderDirs)\\n        // Ensure header appears after shebang if p